          adult: "\"You shall worship the Lord your God and him only shall you serve.\" The first commandment embraces faith, hope, and charity: faith obliges us to believe in God and guard against voluntary doubt, incredulity, heresy, apostasy, and schism; hope forbids both despair and presumption; charity requires that we love God above everything, rejecting indifference, ingratitude, lukewarmness, acedia, and hatred of God (CCC 2086-2094). The virtue of religion renders God what we owe him: adoration, prayer, sacrifice, and the keeping of promises and vows (CCC 2095-2103). Against this the Catechism names superstition, idolatry (which divinizes what is not God, whether demons, power, pleasure, race, ancestors, the state, or money), divination and magic in all their forms (horoscopes, astrology, palm reading, mediums, recourse to occult powers), and irreligion such as tempting God, sacrilege, and simony (CCC 2110-2121). Atheism, in its many forms, contradicts the first commandment, though believers may share responsibility for it by teaching or living the faith badly; agnosticism can express a certain search for God but is all too often a practical atheism (CCC 2123-2128). Finally, the Christian veneration of sacred images is not idolatry: based on the Incarnation of the Word, the honor paid to an image passes to its prototype, so whoever venerates an image venerates the person portrayed in it (CCC 2129-2132)."
